            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>What little remains of the ogham inscription would appear to correspond with another possible personal name on CIIC 129. Cooldorragha, Co. Cork (VEQOANAI MAQI EQOD[...) <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                        <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >127-8</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. EQODD[I] <hi rend="italic">ech</hi> 'horse'? <ref
                                target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                    >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">122</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p><q>The spelling <hi rend="italic">Finten</hi> for the later <hi rend="italic">Fintan</hi> is consevative and implies a comparatively early date, perhaps seventh- or early eighth century... 
                        While it is possible that a later reading of the text may have inspired the dedication of Kilfountain/<hi rend="italic">Cill Fionntain</hi>, it is more likely that the text is a dedicatory one, recording the donation or dedication of the 
                        site to the eponymous saint, although to which of the many St Fintans is not known</q>. A comparable case would be the stone probably inscribed SCI BRECANI, also in half-uncial, at Kilbrecan, Aran Mór (<ref type="bibliog" target="#OKA2001"
                            ><bibl><author>Okasha and Forsyth</author>
                                <date when="2001">2001</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >163-4</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p></item></list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Standing at the site, probably in the same position it is in today, in the townland of <placeName type="townland">Kilfountain</placeName> and barony of <placeName
                                type="barony">Corkaguiney</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-10.306496, 52.157768</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location probably original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">The stone is standing in a pile of quartz rubble to the east of the ruined oratory <ref
                            target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=KE043-144005-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>The stone was first recorded by Windele in September 1848 (<ref type="bibliog" target="#OKA2001"
                    ><bibl><author>Okasha and Forsyth</author>
                        <date when="2001">2001</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >161</biblScope></bibl></ref>). It was last recorded for the Ogham in 3D project in 2016 by Emmy Van Den Berg, a participant on the Corca Dhuibhne 3d project, using Structure from Motion 3d technology (photographs also by Emmy).</p>
            </div>
